RS annexure converter — content ppm extraction logic fix (product-agnostic). This is an annexure level issue too which u never solved or addressed

Bug at converter level: converted_ppm is unreliable when raw_text contains
both a batch actual value and a spec limit. Converter behavior is
inconsistent across compendia and vendors, sometimes picking actual, sometimes
picking spec. Downstream cannot recover correct value if converter emits
wrong number.

Universal logical rule for converter ppm extraction:

Every extracted solvent statement should be classified into ONE of these
evidence categories, based on raw_text content only (not on vendor identity
or compendial context):

Category A — Spec limit only:
- Raw text contains "NMT", "Not more than", "≤", "no más de", "maximum",
or explicit limit language WITHOUT a paired lower measured value
- converted_ppm = the numeric spec limit
- evidence_type = "nmt"

Category B — Batch actual only:
- Raw text contains a single numeric value with no NMT context
- Optional labels: "Actual", "Result", "Content", "Found", "Measured"
- converted_ppm = the numeric value
- evidence_type = "batch_actual"

Category C — Batch actual + spec limit both present:
- Raw text contains two numeric values in a range pattern
- Common formats: "X - Y", "X to Y", "X ppm - Y ppm", "X (< Y)", "X < Y",
tabular "Actual | Spec" columns rendered as "X | NMT Y"
- Convention: smaller value = batch actual, larger value = spec limit
- Rule: converted_ppm = spec limit (larger value) for worst-case exposure
- Preserve actual_measured_ppm = smaller value for audit
- evidence_type = "nmt"
- calculation_basis = "nmt_with_batch_actual"

Category D — BDL/BQL/ND with associated spec:
- Raw text contains "BDL", "BQL", "ND", "Not detected", "< LOD", "< LOQ"
paired with an NMT spec elsewhere in same statement
- converted_ppm = the spec limit for worst-case
- evidence_type = "nmt_conservative_bdl"
- Add note: "BDL result; using spec limit for worst-case exposure"

Category E — BDL/BQL/ND without spec:
- BDL/BQL/ND with no spec available in raw_text
- converted_ppm = null
- evidence_type = "unresolved_bdl"
- Add manual review flag

Category F — Negative declaration:
- Raw text contains "not used", "excluded", "0 ppm", "none present",
"no source", "not employed"
- converted_ppm = 0
- evidence_type = "negative_declaration"

Category G — Ambiguous:
- Cannot classify into A-F reliably
- converted_ppm = null
- evidence_type = "ambiguous"
- Add manual review flag

Universal extraction algorithm (product-agnostic, vendor-agnostic,
compendium-agnostic):

Step 1: Extract all numeric values from raw_text (with units when adjacent).
Step 2: Detect keyword context:
- NMT context: "NMT", "Not more than", "maximum", "≤", "at most"
- Actual context: "Actual", "Result", "Content", "Found", "Measured",
"Analysis", "Test result"
- BDL context: "BDL", "BQL", "ND", "Not detected", "< LOD", "< LOQ"
- Negative context: "not used", "excluded", "0 ppm", "not present"
- Range delimiters: "-", "to", "|", "/", "<"

Step 3: Apply classification:
- Zero numeric values + negative context → Category F
- Zero numeric values + BDL context → Category E
- One numeric value + NMT context → Category A
- One numeric value + no context → Category B
- One numeric value + BDL context → Category D (search for paired spec)
- Two numeric values + range delimiter → Category C
- Two numeric values without range delimiter → analyze which has NMT context
- More than two numeric values → identify primary spec limit, treat others
as audit only

Step 4: Set converted_ppm per category rules.

Step 5: Preserve full audit trail:
{
converted_ppm: [selected value],
actual_measured_ppm: [batch actual if extracted, else null],
spec_limit_ppm: [spec limit if extracted, else null],
evidence_type: [category label],
raw_text: [original text],
extraction_notes: [algorithm reasoning]
}

Multi-compendial handling within one annexure (existing rule, preserved):
When multiple entries exist for same canonical solvent from same annexure:
- Priority 1: USP/USP-NF variant
- Priority 2: Ph.Eur/EP variant
- Priority 3: JP variant
- Priority 4: ASMF/in-house variant
Store non-primary entries in _superseded array for audit.
Each _superseded entry also follows Category A-G classification.

